# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: demand-response-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Utilities may signal demand requests to their customers in a variety of ways, including simple off-peak metering, in which power is cheaper at certain times of the day, and smart metering, in which explicit requests or changes in price can be communicated to customers.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The customer may adjust power demand by postponing some tasks that require large amounts of electric power, or may decide to pay a higher price for their electricity.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Some customers may switch part of their consumption to alternate sources, such as on-site solar panels and batteries.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In many respects, demand response can be put simply as a technology-enabled economic rationing system for electric power supply.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In demand response, voluntary rationing is accomplished by price incentives—offering lower net unit pricing in exchange for reduced power consumption in peak periods.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The direct implication is that users of electric power capacity not reducing usage (load) during peak periods will pay "surge" unit prices, whether directly, or factored into general rates.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Involuntary rationing, if employed, would be accomplished via rolling blackouts during peak load periods.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Practically speaking, summer heat waves and winter deep freezes might be characterized by planned power outages for consumers and businesses if voluntary rationing via incentives fails to reduce load adequately to match total power supply.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In 2013, it was expected that demand response programs will be designed to decrease electricity consumption or shift it from on-peak to off-peak periods depending on consumers' preferences and lifestyles.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In 2016 demand response was defined as "a wide range of actions which can be taken at the customer side of the electricity meter in response to particular conditions within the electricity system such as peak period network congestion or high prices".
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In 2010, demand response was defined as a reduction in demand designed to reduce peak demand or avoid system emergencies.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] It can be a more cost-effective alternative than adding generation capabilities to meet the peak and occasional demand spikes.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The underlying objective of DR is to actively engage customers in modifying their consumption in response to pricing signals.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The goal is to reflect supply expectations through consumer price signals or controls and enable dynamic changes in consumption relative to price.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In electricity grids, DR is similar to dynamic demand mechanisms to manage customer consumption of electricity in response to supply conditions, for example, having electricity customers reduce their consumption at critical times or in response to market prices.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The difference is that demand response mechanisms respond to explicit requests to shut off, whereas dynamic demand devices passively shut off when stress in the grid is sensed.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Demand response can involve actually curtailing power used or by starting on-site generation which may or may not be connected in parallel with the grid.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] This is a quite different concept from energy efficiency, which means using less power to perform the same tasks, on a continuous basis or whenever that task is performed.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] At the same time, demand response is a component of smart energy demand, which also includes energy efficiency, home and building energy management, distributed renewable resources, and electric vehicle charging.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Current demand response schemes are implemented with large and small commercial as well as residential customers, often through the use of dedicated control systems to shed loads in response to a request by a utility or market price conditions.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Services (lights, machines, air conditioning) are reduced according to a preplanned load prioritization scheme during the critical time frames.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] An alternative to load shedding is on-site generation of electricity to supplement the power grid.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Under conditions of tight electricity supply, demand response can significantly decrease the peak price and, in general, electricity price volatility.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Demand response is generally used to refer to mechanisms used to encourage consumers to reduce demand, thereby reducing the peak demand for electricity.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Since electrical generation and transmission systems are generally sized to correspond to peak demand (plus margin for forecasting error and unforeseen events), lowering peak demand reduces overall plant and capital cost requirements.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Depending on the configuration of generation capacity, however, demand response may also be used to increase demand (load) at times of high production and low demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Some systems may thereby encourage energy storage to arbitrage between periods of low and high demand (or low and high prices).
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Bitcoin mining is an electricity intensive process to convert computer hardware infrastructure, software skills and electricity into electronic currency.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Bitcoin mining is used to increase the demand during surplus hours by consuming cheaper power.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] There are three types of demand response - emergency demand response, economic demand response and ancillary services demand response.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Emergency demand response is employed to avoid involuntary service interruptions during times of supply scarcity.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Economic demand response is employed to allow electricity customers to curtail their consumption when the productivity or convenience of consuming that electricity is worth less to them than paying for the electricity.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Ancillary services demand response consists of a number of specialty services that are needed to ensure the secure operation of the transmission grid and which have traditionally been provided by generators.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In most electric power systems, some or all consumers pay a fixed price per unit of electricity independent of the cost of production at the time of consumption.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The consumer price may be established by the government or a regulator, and typically represents an average cost per unit of production over a given timeframe (for example, a year).
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Consumption therefore is not sensitive to the cost of production in the short term (e.g. on an hourly basis).
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] A pure economist might extrapolate the concept to hypothesize that consumers served under these fixed-rate tariffs are endowed with theoretical "call options" on electricity, though in reality, like any other business, the customer is simply buying what is on offer at the agreed price.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] A customer in a department store buying a $10 item at 9.00 am might notice 10 sales staff on the floor but only one occupied serving him or her, while at 3.00 pm the customer could buy the same $10 article and notice all 10 sales staff occupied.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In virtually all power systems electricity is produced by generators that are dispatched in merit order, i.e., generators with the lowest marginal cost (lowest variable cost of production) are used first, followed by the next cheapest, etc., until the instantaneous electricity demand is satisfied.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In most power systems the wholesale price of electricity will be equal to the marginal cost of the highest cost generator that is injecting energy, which will vary with the level of demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Thus the variation in pricing can be significant: for example, in Ontario between August and September 2006, wholesale prices (in Canadian Dollars) paid to producers ranged from a peak of $318 per MW·h to a minimum of - (negative) $3.10 per MW·h.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] It is not unusual for the price to vary by a factor of two to five due to the daily demand cycle.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] A negative price indicates that producers were being charged to provide electricity to the grid (and consumers paying real-time pricing may have actually received a rebate for consuming electricity during this period).
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] This generally occurs at night when demand falls to a level where all generators are operating at their minimum output levels and some of them must be shut down.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The negative price is the inducement to bring about these shutdowns in a least-cost manner.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The latter study found that even small shifts in peak demand would have a large effect on savings to consumers and avoided costs for additional peak capacity: a 1% shift in peak demand would result in savings of 3.9%, billions of dollars at the system level.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] An approximately 10% reduction in peak demand (achievable depending on the elasticity of demand) would result in systems savings of between $8 and $28 billion.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] While the net benefits would be significantly less than the claimed $35 billion, they would still be quite substantial.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In Ontario, Canada, the Independent Electricity System Operator has noted that in 2006, peak demand exceeded 25,000 megawatts during only 32 system hours (less than 0.4% of the time), while maximum demand during the year was just over 27,000 megawatts.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The ability to "shave" peak demand based on reliable commitments would therefore allow the province to reduce built capacity by approximately 2,000 megawatts.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In an electricity grid, electricity consumption and production must balance at all times; any significant imbalance could cause grid instability or severe voltage fluctuations, and cause failures within the grid.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Total generation capacity is therefore sized to correspond to total peak demand with some margin of error and allowance for contingencies (such as plants being off-line during peak demand periods).
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Operators will generally plan to use the least expensive generating capacity (in terms of marginal cost) at any given period, and use additional capacity from more expensive plants as demand increases.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Demand response in most cases is targeted at reducing peak demand to reduce the risk of potential disturbances, avoid additional capital cost requirements for additional plants, and avoid use of more expensive or less efficient operating plants.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Consumers of electricity will also pay higher prices if generation capacity is used from a higher-cost source of power generation.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Demand response may also be used to increase demand during periods of high supply and low demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Some types of generating plant must be run at close to full capacity (such as nuclear), while other types may produce at negligible marginal cost (such as wind and solar).
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Since there is usually limited capacity to store energy, demand response may attempt to increase load during these periods to maintain grid stability.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] For example, in the province of Ontario in September 2006, there was a short period of time when electricity prices were negative for certain users.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Energy storage such as pumped-storage hydroelectricity is a way to increase load during periods of low demand for use during later periods.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Use of demand response to increase load is less common, but may be necessary or efficient in systems where there are large amounts of generating capacity that cannot be easily cycled down.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Some grids may use pricing mechanisms that are not real-time, but easier to implement (users pay higher prices during the day and lower prices at night, for example) to provide some of the benefits of the demand response mechanism with less demanding technological requirements.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In the UK, Economy 7 and similar schemes that attempt to shift demand associated with electric heating to overnight off-peak periods have been in operation since the 1970s.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] More recently, in 2006 Ontario began implementing a "smart meter" program that implements "time-of-use" (TOU) pricing, which tiers pricing according to on-peak, mid-peak and off-peak schedules.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] During the winter, on-peak is defined as morning and early evening, mid-peak as midday to late afternoon, and off-peak as nighttime; during the summer, the on-peak and mid-peak periods are reversed, reflecting air conditioning as the driver of summer demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] As of May 1, 2015, most Ontario electrical utilities have completed converting all customers to "smart meter" time-of-use billing with on-peak rates about 200% and mid-peak rates about 150% of the off-peak rate per kWh.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Australia has national standards for Demand Response (AS/NZS 4755 series), which has been implemented nationwide by electricity distributors for several decades, e.g. controlling storage water heaters, air conditioners and pool pumps.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In 2016, how to manage electrical energy storage (e.g., batteries) has been added into the series of standards.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Energy consumers need some incentive to respond to such a request from a demand response provider.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Demand response incentives can be formal or informal.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The utility might create a tariff-based incentive by passing along short-term increases in the price of electricity, or they might impose mandatory cutbacks during a heat wave for selected high-volume users, who are compensated for their participation.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Other users may receive a rebate or other incentive based on firm commitments to reduce power during periods of high demand, sometimes referred to as *negawatts* (the term was coined by Amory Lovins in 1985).
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] For example, California introduced its own ELRP, where upon an emergency declaration enrolled customers get a credit for lowering their electricity use ($1 per kWh in 2021, $2 in 2022).
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Commercial and industrial power users might impose load shedding on themselves, without a request from the utility.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Some businesses generate their own power and wish to stay within their energy production capacity to avoid buying power from the grid.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Some utilities have commercial tariff structures that set a customer's power costs for the month based on the customer's moment of highest use, or peak demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] This encourages users to flatten their demand for energy, known as energy demand management, which sometimes requires cutting back services temporarily.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Smart metering has been implemented in some jurisdictions to provide real-time pricing for all types of users, as opposed to fixed-rate pricing throughout the demand period.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In this application, users have a direct incentive to reduce their use at high-demand, high-price periods.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Many users may not be able to effectively reduce their demand at various times, or the peak prices may be lower than the level required to induce a change in demand during short time periods (users have low price sensitivity, or elasticity of demand is low).
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Automated control systems exist, which, although effective, may be too expensive to be feasible for some applications.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Smart grid applications improve the ability of electricity producers and consumers to communicate with one another and make decisions about how and when to produce and consume electrical power.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] This emerging technology will allow customers to shift from an event-based demand response where the utility requests the shedding of load, towards a more 24/7-based demand response where the customer sees incentives for controlling load all the time.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Although this back-and-forth dialogue increases the opportunities for demand response, customers are still largely influenced by economic incentives and are reluctant to relinquish total control of their assets to utility companies.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] One advantage of a smart grid application is time-based pricing.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Customers who traditionally pay a fixed rate for consumed energy (kWh) and requested peak load can set their threshold and adjust their usage to take advantage of fluctuating prices.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] This may require the use of an energy management system to control appliances and equipment and can involve economies of scale.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Another advantage, mainly for large customers with generation, is being able to closely monitor, shift, and balance load in a way that allows the customer to save peak load and not only save on kWh and kW/month but be able to trade what they have saved in an energy market.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Again, this involves sophisticated energy management systems, incentives, and a viable trading market.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Smart grid applications increase the opportunities for demand response by providing real time data to producers and consumers, but the economic and environmental incentives remain the driving force behind the practice.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] One of the most important means of demand response in the future smart grids is electric vehicles.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Aggregation of this new source of energy, which is also a new source of uncertainty in the electrical systems, is critical to preserving the stability and quality of smart grids, consequently, the electric vehicle parking lots can be considered a demand response aggregation entity.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The modern power grid is making a transition from the traditional vertically integrated utility structures to distributed systems as it begins to integrate higher penetrations of renewable energy generation.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] These sources of energy are often diffusely distributed and intermittent by nature.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] These features introduce problems in grid stability and efficiency which lead to limitations on the amount of these resources which can be effectively added to the grid.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In a traditional vertically integrated grid, energy is provided by utility generators which are able to respond to changes in demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Generation output by renewable resources is governed by environmental conditions and is generally not able to respond to changes in demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Responsive control over noncritical loads that are connected to the grid has been shown to be an effective strategy able to mitigate undesirable fluctuations introduced by these renewable resources.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In this way instead of the generation responding to changes in demand, the demand responds to changes in generation.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In order to implement demand response systems, coordination of large numbers of distributed resources through sensors, actuators, and communications protocols becomes necessary.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] To be effective, the devices need to be economical, robust, and yet still effective at managing their tasks of control.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In addition, effective control requires a strong capability to coordinate large networks of devices, managing and optimizing these distributed systems from both an economic and a security standpoint.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In addition, the increased presence of variable renewable generation drives a greater need for authorities to procure more ancillary services for grid balance.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] One of these services is contingency reserve, which is used to regulate the grid frequency in contingencies.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] As the ratio of inverter-based generation compared to conventional generation increases, the mechanical inertia used to stabilize frequency decreases.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] When coupled with the sensitivity of inverter-based generation to transient frequencies, the provision of ancillary services from other sources than generators becomes increasingly important.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Technologies are available, and more are under development, to automate the process of demand response.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Such technologies detect the need for load shedding, communicate the demand to participating users, automate load shedding, and verify compliance with demand-response programs.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] GridWise and EnergyWeb are two major federal initiatives in the United States to develop these technologies.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Universities and private industry are also doing research and development in this arena.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Scalable and comprehensive software solutions for DR enable business and industry growth.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Some utilities are considering and testing automated systems connected to industrial, commercial and residential users that can reduce consumption at times of peak demand, essentially delaying draw marginally.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Although the amount of demand delayed may be small, the implications for the grid (including financial) may be substantial, since system stability planning often involves building capacity for extreme peak demand events, plus a margin of safety in reserve.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Such events may only occur a few times per year.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The process may involve turning down or off certain appliances or sinks (and, when demand is unexpectedly low, potentially increasing usage).
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] For example, heating may be turned down or air conditioning or refrigeration may be turned up (turning up to a higher temperature uses less electricity), delaying slightly the draw until a peak in usage has passed.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Although this is an experimental program, at scale these solutions have the potential to reduce peak demand considerably.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The success of such programs depends on the development of appropriate technology, a suitable pricing system for electricity, and the cost of the underlying technology.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Bonneville Power experimented with direct-control technologies in Washington and Oregon residences, and found that the avoided transmission investment would justify the cost of the technology.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Other methods to implementing demand response approach the issue of subtly reducing duty cycles rather than implementing thermostat setbacks.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] These can be implemented using customized building automation systems programming, or through swarm-logic methods coordinating multiple loads in a facility (e.g.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Similar approach can be implemented for managing air conditioning peak demand in summer peak regions.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Pre-cooling or maintaining slightly higher thermostat setting can help with the peak demand reduction.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In 2008 it was announced that electric refrigerators will be sold in the UK sensing dynamic demand which will delay or advance the cooling cycle based on monitoring grid frequency but they are not readily available as of 2018.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Industrial customers are also providing demand response.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] For example, Alcoa's Warrick Operation is participating in MISO as a qualified demand response resource, and the Trimet Aluminium uses its smelter as a short-term nega-battery.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The selection of suitable industries for demand response provision is typically based on an assessment of the so-called value of lost load.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Some data centers are located far apart for redundancy and can migrate loads between them, while also performing demand response.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Shedding loads during peak demand is important because it reduces the need for new power plants.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] To respond to high peak demand, utilities build very capital-intensive power plants and lines.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Peak demand happens just a few times a year, so those assets run at a mere fraction of their capacity.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Electric users pay for this idle capacity through the prices they pay for electricity.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] According to the Demand Response Smart Grid Coalition, 10%–20% of electricity costs in the United States are due to peak demand during only 100 hours of the year.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] DR is a way for utilities to reduce the need for large capital expenditures, and thus keep rates lower overall; however, there is an economic limit to such reductions because consumers lose the productive or convenience value of the electricity not consumed.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Thus, it is misleading to only look at the cost savings that demand response can produce without also considering what the consumer gives up in the process.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] It is estimated that a 5% lowering of demand would have resulted in a 50% price reduction during the peak hours of the California electricity crisis in 2000–2001.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] With consumers facing peak pricing and reducing their demand, the market should become more resilient to intentional withdrawal of offers from the supply side.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Residential and commercial electricity use often vary drastically during the day, and demand response attempts to reduce the variability based on pricing signals.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Electric systems and grids typically scale total potential production to meet projected peak demand (with sufficient spare capacity to deal with unanticipated events).
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] By "smoothing" demand to reduce peaks, less investment in operational reserve will be required, and existing facilities will operate more frequently.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] In addition, significant peaks may only occur rarely, such as two or three times per year, requiring significant capital investments to meet infrequent events.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The report estimates that in 2004 potential demand response capability equaled about 20,500 megawatts (MW), 3% of total U.S. peak demand, while actual delivered peak demand reduction was about 9,000 MW (1.3% of peak), leaving ample margin for improvement.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] It is further estimated that load management capability has fallen by 32% since 1996.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Factors affecting this trend include fewer utilities offering load management services, declining enrollment in existing programs, the changing role and responsibility of utilities, and changing supply/demand balance.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] To encourage the use and implementation of demand response in the United States, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) issued Order No.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] 745 in March 2011, which requires a certain level of compensation for providers of economic demand response that participate in wholesale power markets.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] The order is highly controversial and has been opposed by a number of energy economists, including Professor William W.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Hogan at Harvard University's Kennedy School.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Professor Hogan asserts that the order overcompensates providers of demand response, thereby encouraging the curtailment of electricity whose economic value exceeds the cost of producing it.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Professor Hogan further asserts that Order No.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] 745 is anticompetitive and amounts to "...an application of regulatory authority to enforce a buyer's cartel." Several affected parties, including the State of California, have filed suit in federal court challenging the legality of Order 745.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] A debate regarding the economic efficiency and fairness of Order 745 appeared in a series of articles published in The Electricity Journal.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Circuit Court of Appeals vacated Order 745 in its entirety.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Whether the Court of Appeals erred in holding that the rule issued by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission is arbitrary and capricious.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] On January 25, 2016, the United States Supreme Court in a 6-2 decision in *FERC v.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Electric Power Supply Ass'n* concluded that the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission acted within its authority to ensure "just and reasonable" rates in the wholesale energy market.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] 2222 on September 17, 2020, enabling distributed energy resources to participate in regional wholesale electricity markets.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Market operators submitted initial compliance plans by early 2022.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] As of December 2009 National Grid had 2369 MW contracted to provide demand response, known as STOR, the demand side provides 839 MW (35%) from 89 sites.
[src:demand-response-systems/automated-demand-response] Of this 839 MW approximately 750 MW is back-up generation with the remaining being load reduction.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In some sectors, economists have characterized dynamic pricing as having welfare improvements over uniform pricing and contributing to more optimal allocation of limited resources.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Its usage often stirs public controversy, as people frequently think of it as price gouging.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Businesses are able to change prices based on algorithms that take into account competitor pricing, supply and demand, and other external factors in the market.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Dynamic pricing is a common practice in several industries such as hospitality, tourism, entertainment, retail, electricity, and public transport.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Each industry takes a slightly different approach to dynamic pricing based on its individual needs and the demand for the product.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Cost-plus pricing is the most basic method of pricing.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] A store will simply charge consumers the cost required to produce a product plus a predetermined amount of profit.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Cost-plus pricing is simple to execute, but it only considers internal information when setting the price and does not factor in external influencers like market reactions, the weather, or changes in consumer value.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] A dynamic pricing tool can make it easier to update prices, but will not make the updates often if the user does not account for external information like competitor market prices.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Due to its simplicity, this is the most widely used method of pricing with around 74% of companies in the United States employing this dynamic pricing strategy.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Although widely used, the usage is skewed, with companies facing a high degree of competition using this strategy the most, on the other hand, companies that deal with manufacturing tend to use this strategy the least.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Businesses that want to price competitively will monitor their competitors' prices and adjust accordingly.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] This is called competitor-based pricing.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In retail, the competitor that many companies watch is Amazon, which changes prices frequently throughout the day.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Amazon is a market leader in retail that changes prices often, which encourages other retailers to alter their prices to stay competitive.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Such online retailers use price-matching mechanisms like price trackers.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The retailers give the end-user an option for the same, and upon selecting the option to price match, an online bot searches for the lowest price across various websites and offers a price lower than the lowest.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Such pricing behavior depends on market conditions, as well as a firm's planning.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Although a firm existing within a highly competitive market is compelled to cut prices, that is not always the case.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In case of high competition, yet a stable market, and a long-term view, it was predicted that firms will tend to cooperate on a price basis rather than undercut each other.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Ideally, companies should ask the price for a product that is equal to the value a consumer attaches to a product.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] As this value can differ from person to person, it is difficult to uncover the perfect value and have a differentiated price for every person.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] However, consumers' willingness to pay can be used as a proxy for the perceived value.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] With the price elasticity of products, companies can calculate how many consumers are willing to pay for the product at each price point.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Products with high elasticities are highly sensitive to changes in price, while products with low elasticities are less sensitive to price changes (ceteris paribus).
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Subsequently, products with low elasticity are typically valued more by consumers if everything else is equal.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The dynamic aspect of this pricing method is that elasticities change with respect to the product, category, time, location, and retailers.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] With the price elasticity of products and the margin of the product, retailers can use this method with their pricing strategy to aim for volume, revenue, or profit maximization strategies.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] There are two types of bundle pricing strategies: one from the consumer's point of view, and one from the seller's point of view.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] From the seller's point of view, an end product's price depends on whether it is bundled with something else; which bundle it belongs to; and sometimes on which customers it is offered to.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] This strategy is adopted by print-media houses and other subscription-based services.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] *The Wall Street Journal*, for example, offers a standalone price if an electronic mode of delivery is purchased, and a discount when it is bundled with print delivery.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Many industries, especially online retailers, change prices depending on the time of day.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Most retail customers shop during weekly office hours (between 9 am and 5 pm), so many retailers will raise prices during the morning and afternoon, then lower prices during the evening.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Peak fit pricing is best used for products that are inelastic in supply, where suppliers are fully able to anticipate demand growth and thus be able to charge differently for service during systematic periods of time.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] A utility with regulated prices may develop a time-based pricing schedule on analysis of its long-run costs, such as operation and investment costs.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] A utility such as electricity (or another service), operating in a market environment, may be auctioned on a competitive market; time-based pricing will typically reflect price variations on the market.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Such variations include both regular oscillations due to the demand patterns of users; supply issues (such as availability of intermittent natural resources like water flow or wind); and exceptional price peaks.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Price peaks reflect strained conditions in the market (possibly augmented by market manipulation, as during the California electricity crisis), and convey a possible lack of investment.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Extreme events include the default by Griddy after the 2021 Texas power crisis.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Time-based pricing is the standard method of pricing in the tourism industry.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Higher prices are charged during the peak season, or during special event periods.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In the off-season, hotels may charge only the operating costs of the establishment, whereas investments and any profit are gained during the high season (this is the basic principle of long-run marginal cost pricing: see also long run and short run).
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Hotels and other players in the hospitality industry use dynamic pricing to adjust the cost of rooms and packages based on the supply and demand needs at a particular moment.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The goal of dynamic pricing in this industry is to find the highest price that consumers are willing to pay.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Another name for dynamic pricing in the industry is demand pricing.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] This form of price discrimination is used to try to maximize revenue based on the willingness to pay of different market segments.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] It features price increases when demand is high and decreases to stimulate demand when it is low.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Having a variety of prices based on the demand at each point in the day makes it possible for hotels to generate more revenue by bringing in customers at the different price points they are willing to pay.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Airlines change prices often depending on the day of the week, time of day, and the number of days before the flight.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] For airlines, dynamic pricing factors in different components such as: how many seats a flight has, departure time, and average cancellations on similar flights.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] A 2022 study in *Econometrica* estimated that dynamic pricing was beneficial for "early-arriving, leisure consumers at the expense of late-arriving, business travelers.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Although dynamic pricing ensures seat availability for business travelers, these consumers are then charged higher prices.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Congestion pricing is often used in public transportation and road pricing, where a higher price at peak periods is used to encourage more efficient use of the service or time-shifting to cheaper or free off-peak travel.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] For example, the San Francisco Bay Bridge charges a higher toll during rush hour and on the weekend, when drivers are more likely to be traveling.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] This is an effective way to boost revenue when demand is high, while also managing demand since drivers unwilling to pay the premium will avoid those times.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The London congestion charge discourages automobile travel to Central London during peak periods.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The Washington Metro and Long Island Rail Road charge higher fares at peak times.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The tolls on the Custis Memorial Parkway vary automatically according to the actual number of cars on the roadway, and at times of severe congestion can reach almost $50.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Dynamic pricing is also used by Uber and Lyft.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Uber's system for "dynamically adjusting prices for service" measures supply (Uber drivers) and demand (passengers hailing rides by use of smartphones), and prices fares accordingly.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Ride-sharing companies such as Uber and Lyft have increasingly incorporated dynamic pricing into their operations.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] This strategy enables these businesses to offer the best prices for both drivers and passengers by adjusting prices in real-time in response to supply and demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] When there is a strong demand for rides, rates go up to encourage more drivers to offer their services, and when there is a low demand, prices go down to draw in more passengers.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Some professional sports teams use dynamic pricing structures to boost revenue.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In the United States, dynamic pricing is particularly important in baseball because Major League Baseball (MLB) teams play around twice as many games as some other sports and in much larger venues.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Sports that are outdoors have to factor weather into pricing strategy, in addition to the date of the game, date of purchase, and opponent.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Tickets for a game during inclement weather will sell better at a lower price; conversely, when a team is on a winning streak, fans will be willing to pay more.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Dynamic pricing was first introduced to sports by a start-up software company Qcue.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] MLB club San Francisco Giants implemented a pilot of 2,000 seats in the View Reserved and Bleachers and moved on to dynamically pricing the entire venue for the 2010 season.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Qcue currently works with two-thirds of MLB franchises, not all of which have implemented a full dynamic pricing structure.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In 2012, the Giants, Oakland Athletics, and St.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Louis Cardinals became the first teams to dynamically price postseason tickets.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] While behind baseball in terms of adoption, the National Basketball Association, National Hockey League, and NCAA have also seen teams implement dynamic pricing.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Outside of the US, it has since been adopted on a trial basis by some clubs in the Football League.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Scottish Premier League club Heart of Midlothian introduced dynamic pricing for the sale of their season tickets in 2012, but supporters complained that they were being charged significantly more than the advertised price.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Retailers, and online retailers, in particular, adjust the price of their products according to competitors, time, traffic, conversion rates, and sales goals.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Supermarkets often use dynamic pricing strategies to manage perishable inventory, such as fresh produce and meat products, that have a limited shelf life.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] By adjusting prices based on factors like expiration dates and current inventory levels, retailers can minimize waste and maximize revenue.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Additionally, the widespread adoption of electronic shelf labels in grocery stores has made it easier to implement dynamic pricing strategies in real-time, enabling retailers to respond quickly to changing market conditions and consumer preferences.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] These labels also make it easier for grocery stores to mark up high demand items (e.g. making it more expensive to purchase ice in warmer weather).
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Theme parks have also recently adopted this pricing model.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Disneyland and Disney World adapted this practice in 2016, and Universal Studios followed suit.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Since the supply of parks is limited and new rides cannot be added based on the surge of demand, the model followed by theme parks in regards to dynamic pricing resembles that followed by the hotel industry.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] During summertime, when demand is rather inelastic, the parks charge higher prices, whereas ticket prices in winter are less expensive.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Dynamic pricing is often criticized as price gouging.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Dynamic pricing is widely unpopular among consumers as some feel it tends to favour particular buyers.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] While the intent of surge pricing is generally driven by demand-supply dynamics, some instances have proven otherwise.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Some businesses utilise modern technologies (Big data and IoT) to adopt dynamic pricing strategies, where collection and analysis of real-time private data occur almost instantaneously.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] As modern technology on data analysis is developing rapidly, enabling to detect one's browsing history, age, gender, location and preference, some consumers fear "unwanted privacy invasions and data fraud" as the extent of their information being used is often undisclosed or ambiguous.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Even with firms' disclaimers stating private information will only be used strictly for data collection and promising no third-party distribution will occur, few cases of misconducting companies can disrupt consumers' perceptions.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Some consumers were simply skeptical on general information collection outright due to the potentiality of "data leakages and misuses", possibly impacting suppliers' long-term profitability stimulated by reduced customer loyalty.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Consumers can also develop price fairness/unfairness perceptions, whereby different prices being offered to individuals for the same products can affect customers' perceptions on price fairness.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Studies discovered easiness of learning other individuals' purchase price induced consumers to sense price unfairness and lower satisfaction when others paid less than themselves.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] However, when consumers were price-advantaged, development of trust and increased repurchase intentions were observed.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Other research indicated price fairness perceptions varied depending on their privacy sensitivity and natures of dynamic pricing like, individual pricing, segment pricing, location data pricing and purchase history pricing.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Amazon engaged in price discrimination for some customers in the year 2000, showing different prices at the same time for the same item to different customers, potentially violating the Robinson–Patman Act.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] When this incident was criticized, Amazon issued a public apology with refunds to almost 7,000 customers but did not cease the practice.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] During the COVID-19 pandemic, prices of certain items in high demand were reported to shoot up by quadruple their original price, garnering negative attention.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Although Amazon denied claims of any such manipulation and blamed a few sellers for shooting up prices for essentials such as sanitizers and masks, prices of essential products 'sold by Amazon' had also seen a hefty rise in prices.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Amazon claimed this was a result of software malfunction.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Uber's surge pricing has also been criticized.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In 2013, when New York was in the midst of a storm, Uber users saw fares go up eight times the usual fares.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] This incident attracted public backlash from public figures, with Salman Rushdie amongst others publicly criticizing this move.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] After this incident, the company started placing caps on how high surge pricing can go during times of emergency, starting in 2015.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Drivers have been known to hold off on accepting rides in an area until surge pricing forces fares up to a level satisfactory to them.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In 2024, Wendy's announced plans to test dynamic pricing in certain American locations during 2025.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] This pricing method was included with plans to redesign menu boards and these changes were announced to stakeholders.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The company received significant online backlash for this decision.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In response, Wendy's stated that the intended implementation was limited to reducing prices during low traffic periods.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The use of dynamic, algorithmic and demand-based pricing in the live music sector has been the subject of considerable controversy.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Ticketmaster introduced dynamic pricing in 2022, and applied it to sale of tickets for tours of Blink-182 (where tickets were priced as high as $600) and Bruce Springsteen (where prices reached $4,000–$5,000).
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In the United Kingdom and Ireland, there was considerable controversy in 2024 over allegations of dynamic pricing by Ticketmaster for the Oasis Live '25 Tour.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Fans made complaints to the Advertising Standards Authority.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Giving evidence to the House of Commons Business and Trade Select Committee, Ticketmaster UK denied they were engaging in dynamic pricing, claiming instead that tickets were offered at "differing price tiers", and pricing was determined by event organisers.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The UK's Competition and Markets Authority launched an investigation into ticket pricing for the Oasis tour, which concluded that Ticketmaster "may have misled Oasis fans" about the price of the tickets.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The European Commission also announced they were to investigate the use of dynamic pricing for concert tickets.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Due to the public backlash over pricing in the UK and Ireland, Oasis announced they would not use dynamic pricing for later legs in the world tour including North America and Australia.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] A number of bands and artists have publicly announced that they are not going to use dynamic ticket pricing including Coldplay, Taylor Swift, Ed Sheeran, Iron Maiden, and Robert Smith from The Cure.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] After their 2020 tour of New Zealand, Crowded House stated they "had no prior knowledge" of dynamic pricing, that they "did not approve" and asked Live Nation to refund the difference in price.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In May 2025, *The Athletic* reported that FIFA will use dynamic pricing for tickets to the men's 2026 FIFA World Cup, as well as the 2025 FIFA Club World Cup.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] It was also used for the 2024 Copa América.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In November 2025, the Colorado Public Utilities Commission approved mandatory time-of-use (TOU) rates for all residential customers of Xcel Energy's Public Service Company of Colorado, effective November 1, 2025.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Under the rate structure, electricity costs approximately $0.213 per kWh during peak hours (5–9 PM on weekdays) and $0.079 per kWh during off-peak hours — a ratio of approximately 2.7:1.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] Colorado became one of the first states to implement mandatory, rather than voluntary, residential TOU pricing for a major investor-owned utility statewide.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The Colorado Public Utilities Commission cited grid demand reduction and the promotion of battery storage and electric vehicle charging during off-peak hours as primary policy goals.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In November, 2025, New York state's "Algorithmic Pricing Disclosure Act" came into effect.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The law requires companies to disclose when prices are set using a consumer's personal data.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The bill enables civil penalties of up to $1,000 per violation.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] In April 2026, Maryland Governor Wes Moore signed HB0895 into law, which bans grocery stores and third-party grocery delivery services from using consumer personal data to raise prices for consumers.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The law authorizes $10,000 penalties for first-time violations and $25,000 for repeat offenses.
[src:demand-response-systems/dynamic-pricing] The law is scheduled to take effect in October 2026.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Due to the complications of electricity generation, the cost to supply electricity varies minute by minute.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Some utility companies are for-profit entities, and their prices include a financial return for owners and investors.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] These utility companies can exercise their political power within existing legal and regulatory regimes to guarantee a financial return and reduce competition from other sources like a distributed generation.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] In standard regulated monopoly markets like the United States, there are multilevel governance structures that set electricity rates.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The rates are determined through a regulatory process that is overseen by governmental organizations.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The inclusion of renewable energy distributed generation (DG) and advanced metering infrastructure (AMI or smart meter) in the modern electricity grid has introduced many alternative rate structures.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The simple rate charges a specific dollar per kilowatt hour ($/kWh) consumed.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The tiered rate is one of the more common residential rate programs.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The tiered rate charges a higher rate as customer usage increases.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] TOU and demand rates are structured to help maintain and control a utility's peak demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The concept at its core is to discourage customers from contributing to peak-load times by charging them more money to use power at that time.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Historically, rates have been minimal at night because the peak is during the day when all sectors are using electricity.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Increased demand requires additional energy generation, which is traditionally provided by less efficient "peaker" plants that cost more to generate electricity than "baseload" plants.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] However, as greater penetration from renewable energy sources, like solar, is on the grid, the lower cost of electricity is shifted to midday when solar generates the most energy.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Time of use (TOU) tariffs can shift electricity consumption out of peak periods, thus helping the grid cope with variable renewable energy.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] A feed-in tariff (FIT) is an energy-supply policy that supports the development of renewable power generation.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] FITs give financial benefits to renewable power producers.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] In the United States, FIT policies guarantee that eligible renewable generators will have their electricity purchased by their utility.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The FIT contract contains a guaranteed period of time (usually 15–20 years) that payments in dollars per kilowatt hour ($/kWh) will be made for the full output of the system.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Net metering is another billing mechanism that supports the development of renewable power generation, specifically, solar power.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The mechanism credits solar energy system owners for the electricity their system adds to the grid.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Residential customers with rooftop photovoltaic (PV) systems will typically generate more electricity than their home consumes during daylight hours, so net metering is particularly advantageous.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] During this time where generation is greater than consumption, the home's electricity meter will run backward to provide a credit on the homeowner's electricity bill.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The value of solar electricity is less than the retail rate, so net metering customers are actually subsidized by all other customers of the electric utility.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] United States: the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) oversees the wholesale electricity market along with the interstate transmission of electricity.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Public Service Commissions (PSC), which are also known as Public Utilities commission (PUC), regulate utility rates within each state.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The cost of electricity also differs by the power source.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The net present value of the unit-cost of electricity over the lifetime of a generating asset is known as the levelized cost of electricity (LCOE).
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] However, LCOE does not account for the system costs, in particular related to the guarantee of grid stability and power quality, which can represent a significant part of the final price of power.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] LCOE is therefore largely insufficient when comparing the costs of different power sources.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The generating source mix of a particular utility will thus have a substantial effect on its electricity pricing.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Electric utilities that have a high percentage of hydroelectricity will tend to have lower prices, while those with a large amount of older coal-fired power plants will have higher electricity prices.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Recently the LCOE of solar photovoltaic technology has dropped substantially.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] In the United States, 70% of current coal-fired power plants run at a higher cost than new renewable energy technologies (excluding hydro) and by 2030 all of them will be uneconomic.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] In the rest of the world 42% of coal-fired power plants were operating at a loss in 2019.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Electricity price forecasting (EPF) is a branch of energy forecasting which focuses on using mathematical, statistical and machine learning models to predict electricity prices in the future.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Over the last 30 years electricity price forecasts have become a fundamental input to energy companies' decision-making mechanisms at the corporate level.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Since the early 1990s, the process of deregulation and the introduction of competitive electricity markets have been reshaping the landscape of the traditionally monopolistic and government-controlled power sectors.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Throughout Europe, North America, Australia and Asia, electricity is now traded under market rules using spot and derivative contracts.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] However, electricity is a very special commodity: it is economically non-storable and power system stability requires a constant balance between production and consumption.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] At the same time, electricity demand depends on weather (temperature, wind speed, precipitation, etc.) and the intensity of business and everyday activities (on-peak vs. off-peak hours, weekdays vs. weekends, holidays, etc.).
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] These unique characteristics lead to price dynamics not observed in any other market, exhibiting daily, weekly and often annual seasonality and abrupt, short-lived and generally unanticipated price spikes.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Extreme price volatility, which can be up to two orders of magnitude higher than that of any other commodity or financial asset, has forced market participants to hedge not only volume but also price risk.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Price forecasts from a few hours to a few months ahead have become of particular interest to power portfolio managers.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] A power market company able to forecast the volatile wholesale prices with a reasonable level of accuracy can adjust its bidding strategy and its own production or consumption schedule in order to reduce the risk or maximize the profits in day-ahead trading.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] A ballpark estimate of savings from a 1% reduction in the mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) of short-term price forecasts is $300,000 per year for a utility with 1GW peak load.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] With the additional price forecasts, the savings double.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] In some markets, electricity price can occasionally be negative.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Excessive Total Harmonic Distortions (THD) and low power factor are costly at every level of the electricity market.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The impact of THD is difficult to estimate, but it can potentially cause heat, vibrations, malfunctioning and even meltdowns.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] The power factor is the ratio of real to apparent power in a power system.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Drawing more current results in a lower power factor.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Larger currents require costlier infrastructure to minimize power loss, so consumers with low power factors get charged a higher electricity rate by their utility.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Power quality is typically monitored at the transmission level.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] A spectrum of compensation devices mitigate bad outcomes, but improvements can be achieved only with real-time correction devices (old style switching type, modern low-speed DSP driven and near real-time).
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Most modern devices reduce problems, while maintaining return on investment and significant reduction of ground currents.
[src:demand-response-systems/electricity-pricing] Power quality problems can cause erroneous responses from many kinds of analog and digital equipment.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Modern utility load management began about 1938, using ripple control.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] By 1948 ripple control was a practical system in wide use.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Czechoslovakia first used ripple control in the 1950s.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Early transmitters were low power, compared to modern systems, only 50 kilovolt-amps.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] They were rotating generators that fed a 1050 Hz signal into transformers attached to power distribution networks.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Early receivers were electromechanical relays.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Later, in the 1970s, transmitters with high-power semiconductors were used.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] These are more reliable because they have no moving parts.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Modern Czech systems send a digital "telegram".
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Each telegram takes about thirty seconds to send.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] There are several formats, used in different districts.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] In 1972, Theodore George "Ted" Paraskevakos, while working for Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system which used digital transmission for security, fire, and medical alarm systems as well as meter-reading capabilities for all utilities.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] This technology was a spin-off of his patented automatic telephone line identification system, now known as caller ID.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] In, 1974, Paraskevakos was awarded a U.S. patent for this technology.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] At the request of the Alabama Power Company, Paraskevakos developed a load-management system along with automatic meter-reading technology.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] In doing so, he utilized the ability of the system to monitor the speed of the watt power meter disc and, consequently, power consumption.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] This information, along with the time of day, gave the power company the ability to instruct individual meters to manage water heater and air conditioning consumption in order to prevent peaks in usage during the high consumption portions of the day.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] For this approach, Paraskevakos was awarded multiple patents.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Since electrical energy is a form of energy that cannot be effectively stored in bulk, it must be generated, distributed, and consumed immediately.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] When the load on a system approaches the maximum generating capacity, network operators must either find additional supplies of energy or find ways to curtail the load, hence load management.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] If they are unsuccessful, the system will become unstable and blackouts can occur.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Long-term load management planning may begin by building sophisticated models to describe the physical properties of the distribution network (i.e. topology, capacity, and other characteristics of the lines), as well as the load behavior.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The analysis may include scenarios that account for weather forecasts, the predicted impact of proposed load-shed commands, estimated time-to-repair for off-line equipment, and other factors.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The utilization of load management can help a power plant achieve a higher capacity factor, a measure of average capacity utilization.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Capacity factor is a measure of the output of a power plant compared to the maximum output it could produce.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Capacity factor is often defined as *the ratio of average load to capacity* or *the ratio of average load to peak load in a period of time*.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] A higher load factor is advantageous because a power plant may be less efficient at low load factors, a high load factor means fixed costs are spread over more kWh of output (resulting in a lower price per unit of electricity), and a higher load factor means greater total output.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] If the power load factor is affected by non-availability of fuel, maintenance shut-down, unplanned breakdown, or reduced demand (as consumption pattern fluctuate throughout the day), the generation has to be adjusted, since grid energy storage is often prohibitively expensive.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Smaller utilities that buy power instead of generating their own find that they can also benefit by installing a load control system.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The penalties they must pay to the energy provider for peak usage can be significantly reduced.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Many report that a load control system can pay for itself in a single season.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] When the decision is made to curtail load, it is done so on the basis of system *reliability*.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The utility in a sense "owns the switch" and sheds loads only when the stability or reliability of the electrical distribution system is threatened.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The utility (being in the business of generating, transporting, and delivering electricity) will not disrupt their business process without due cause.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Load management, when done properly, is non-invasive, and imposes no hardship on the consumer.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The load should be shifted to off peak hours.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Demand response places the "on-off switch" in the hands of the consumer using devices such as a smart grid controlled load control switch.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] While many residential consumers pay a flat rate for electricity year-round, the utility's costs actually vary constantly, depending on demand, the distribution network, and composition of the company's electricity generation portfolio.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] In a free market, the wholesale price of energy varies widely throughout the day.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Demand response programs such as those enabled by smart grids attempt to incentivize the consumer to limit usage based upon *cost* concerns.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] As costs rise during the day (as the system reaches peak capacity and more expensive peaking power plants are used), a free market economy should allow the price to rise.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] A corresponding drop in demand for the commodity should meet a fall in price.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] While this works for predictable shortages, many crises develop within seconds due to unforeseen equipment failures.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] They must be resolved in the same time-frame in order to avoid a power blackout.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Many utilities who are interested in demand response have also expressed an interest in load control capability so that they might be able to operate the "on-off switch" before price updates could be published to the consumers.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The application of load control technology continues to grow today with the sale of both radio frequency and powerline communication based systems.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Certain types of smart meter systems can also serve as load control systems.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Charge control systems can prevent the recharging of electric vehicles during peak hours.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Vehicle-to-grid systems can return electricity from an electric vehicle's batteries to the utility, or they can throttle the recharging of the vehicle batteries to a slower rate.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Ripple control is a common form of load control, and is used in many countries around the world, including the United States, Australia, Czech Republic, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Germany, the Netherlands, and South Africa.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Ripple control involves superimposing a higher-frequency signal (usually between 100 and 1600 Hz) onto the standard 50–60 Hz of the main power signal.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] When receiver devices attached to non-essential residential or industrial loads receive this signal, they shut down the load until the signal is disabled or another frequency signal is received.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Early implementations of ripple control occurred during World War II in various parts of the world using a system that communicates over the electrical distribution system.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Early systems used rotating generators attached to distribution networks through transformers.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Ripple control systems are generally paired with a two- (or more) tiered pricing system, whereby electricity is more expensive during peak times (evenings) and cheaper during low-usage times (early morning).
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Affected residential devices will vary by region, but may include residential electric hot-water heaters, air conditioners, pool pumps, or crop-irrigation pumps.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] In a distribution network outfitted with load control, these devices are outfitted with communicating controllers that can run a program that limits the duty cycle of the equipment under control.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Consumers are usually rewarded for participating in the load control program by paying a reduced rate for energy.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Proper load management by the utility allows them to practice load shedding to avoid rolling blackouts and reduce costs.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Ripple Control is also used to turn off photovoltaic systems in case of electricity overproduction.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Ripple control can be unpopular because sometimes devices can fail to receive the signal to turn on comfort equipment, e.g. hot water heaters or baseboard electrical heaters.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Modern electronic receivers are more reliable than old electromechanical systems.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Also, some modern systems repeat the telegrams to turn on comfort devices.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Also, by popular demand, many ripple control receivers have a switch to force comfort devices on.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Modern ripple controls send a digital telegram, from 30 to 180 seconds long.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Originally these were received by electromechanical relays.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Now they are often received by microprocessors.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Many systems repeat telegrams to assure that comfort devices (e.g. water heaters) are turned on.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Since the broadcast frequencies are in the range of human hearing, they often vibrate wires, filament light-bulbs or transformers in an audible way.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The telegrams follow different standards in different areas.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] For example, in the Czech Republic, different districts use "ZPA II 32S", "ZPA II 64S" and Versacom.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] ZPA II 32S sends a 2.33 second on, a 2.99 second off, then 32 one-second pulses (either on or off), with an "off time" between each pulse of one second.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] ZPA II 64S has a much shorter off time, permitting 64 pulses to be sent, or skipped.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Nearby regions use different frequencies or telegrams, to assure that telegrams operate only in the desired region.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The transformers that attach local grids to interties intentionally do not have the equipment (bridging capacitors) to pass ripple control signals into long-distance power lines.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Each data pulse of a telegram could double the number of commands, so that 32 pulses permit 2^32 distinct commands.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] However, in practice, particular pulses are linked to particular types of device or service.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] For example most ripple control systems have a telegram to set clocks in attached devices, e.g. to midnight.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Zellweger off-peak is one common brand of ripple control systems.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] In recent years, radio-based load management (sometimes known as "**radio ripple control**") signalling systems have been introduced to replace traditional power wire ripple signalling systems.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Some radio-based load management systems have been criticised for lacking sufficient security measures, potentially compromising power grid security or allowing street lighting to be turned on or off.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Greater loads physically slow the rotors of a grid's synchronized generators.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] This causes AC mains to have a slightly reduced frequency when a grid is heavily loaded.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The reduced frequency is immediately sensible across the entire grid.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Inexpensive local electronics can easily and precisely measure mains frequencies and turn off sheddable loads.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] In some cases, this feature is nearly free, e.g. if the controlling equipment (such as an electric power meter, or the thermostat in an air-conditioning system) already has a microcontroller.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Most electronic electric power meters internally measure frequency, and require only demand control relays to turn off equipment.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] In other equipment, often the only needed extra equipment is a resistor divider to sense the mains cycle and a schmitt trigger (a small integrated circuit) so the microcontrollers' digital input can sense a reliable fast digital edge.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] A schmitt trigger is already standard equipment on many microcontrollers.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The main advantage over ripple control is greater customer convenience: Unreceived ripple control telegrams can cause a water heater to remain off, causing a cold shower.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Or, they can cause an airconditioner to remain off, resulting in a sweltering home.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] In contrast, as the grid recovers, its frequency naturally rises to normal, so frequency-controlled load control automatically enables water heaters, air-conditioners and other comfort equipment.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The cost of equipment can be less, and there are no concerns about overlapping or unreached ripple control regions, mis-received codes, transmitter power, etc.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The main disadvantage compared to ripple control is a less fine-grained control.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] For example, a grid authority has only a limited ability to select which loads are shed.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] In controlled war-time economies, this can be a substantial disadvantage.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The system was invented in PNNL in the early 21st century, and has been shown to stabilize grids.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The largest residential load control system in the world is found in Florida and is managed by Florida Power and Light.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] It utilizes 800,000 load control transponders (LCTs) and controls 1,000 MW of electrical power (2,000 MW in an emergency).
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] FPL has been able to avoid the construction of numerous new power plants due to their load management programs.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Since the 1950s, Australia and New Zealand have had a system of load management based on ripple control, allowing the electricity supply for domestic and commercial water storage heaters to be switched off and on, as well as allowing remote control of nightstore heaters and street lights.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Ripple injection equipment located within each local distribution network signals to ripple control receivers at the customer's premises.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Control may either done manually by the local distribution network company in response to local outages or requests to reduce demand from the transmission system operator (i.e.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Transpower), or automatically when injection equipment detects mains frequency falling below 49.2 Hz.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Ripple control receivers are assigned to one of several ripple channels to allow the network company to only turn off supply on part of the network, and to allow staged restoration of supply to reduce the impact of a surge in demand when power is restored to water heaters after a period of time off.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Depending on the area, the consumer may have two electricity meters, one for normal supply ("Anytime") and one for the load-managed supply ("Controlled"), with Controlled supply billed at a lower rate per kilowatt-hour than Anytime supply.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] For those with load-managed supply but only a single meter, electricity is billed at the "Composite" rate, priced between Anytime and Controlled.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The Czechs have operated ripple control systems since the 1950s.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] France has an EJP tariff, which allows it to disconnect certain loads and to encourage consumers to disconnect certain loads.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] This tariff is no longer available for new clients (as of July 2009).
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The *Tempo* tariff also includes different types of days with different prices, but has been discontinued for new clients as well (as of July 2009).
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Reduced prices during nighttime are available for customers for a higher monthly fee.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The distribution system operator Westnetz and gridX piloted a load management solution.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] The solution enables the grid operator to communicate with local energy management systems and adjust the available load for EV charging in response to the state of the grid.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] Rltec in the UK in 2009 reported that domestic refrigerators are being sold fitted with their dynamic load response systems.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] In 2011 it was announced that the Sainsbury supermarket chain will use dynamic demand technology on their heating and ventilation equipment.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] In the UK, night storage heaters are often used with a time-switched off-peak supply option - Economy 7 or Economy 10.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] There is also a programme that allows industrial loads to be disconnected using circuit breakers triggered automatically by frequency sensitive relays fitted on site.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] This operates in conjunction with Standing Reserve, a programme using diesel generators.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] These can also be remotely switched using BBC Radio 4 Longwave Radio teleswitch.
[src:demand-response-systems/load-management] SP transmission deployed Dynamic Load Management scheme in Dumfries and Galloway area using real time monitoring of embedded generation and disconnecting them, should an overload be detected on the transmission Network.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Some utilities will charge customers based on their individual peak demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] The highest demand during each month or even a single 15 to 30 minute period of highest use in the previous year may be used to calculate charges.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] The renewable energy transition will include considerations for peak demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Electricity network is built to deal with the highest possible peak demand otherwise blackout may happen.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] In Australia, demand tariff has three components: peak demand charge, energy charge and daily connection charge.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] For example, for large customers (commercial, industrial or mixed of commercial/residential), the peak demand charge is based on the highest 30 minutes electricity consumption in a month; the energy charge is based on a month electricity consumption.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] This type of demand tariff is gradually introduced to residential households and will be rolled out by 2020 in Queensland Australia.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] How to manage electricity bills under demand tariff can be challenging.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] The key solutions involve improving building efficiency and managing the operational settings of large power appliances.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Peak Demand depends on the demography, the economy, the weather, the climate, the season, the day of the week and other factors.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] In industrialised regions of China or Germany, the peak demands mostly occur in day time.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] However, in more service based economy such as Australia, the daily peak demands often occur in the late afternoon to early evening time (e.g.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Residential and commercial electricity demand contributes a lot to this type of network peak demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Peak demand is considered to be the opposite to off-peak hours when power demand is usually low.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Sometimes, there are 3 time-of-use zones: peak, shoulder and offpeak.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Shoulder is often the time between peak and offpeak in weekdays.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Weekends are often just peak and offpeak in terms of managing electricity loads for the network.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Peak demand may exceed the maximum supply levels that the electrical power industry can generate, resulting in power outages and load shedding.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] This often occurs during heat waves when use of air conditioners and powered fans raises the rate of energy consumption significantly.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] During a shortage authorities may request the public to curtail their energy use and shift it to a non-peak period.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Power stations specifically constructed for providing power to electrical grids for peak demand are called peaking power plants or 'peakers'.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] In general, Natural gas fueled power stations can be fired up rapidly and are therefore often utilized at peak demand times.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Combined cycle power plants can frequently provide power for peak demand, as well as run efficiently for baseload power.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Hydroelectric power and pumped storage type dams such as Carters Dam in the U.S. state of Georgia help to meet peak demand as well.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] The chances that a wind farm will be unable to meet peak demand are greater than for a fossil-fueled power station, due to the ability to store liquid fuels for use during peak demand.
[src:demand-response-systems/peak-demand] Solar power's peak output often naturally coincides with daytime peaks of usage due to air conditioning.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] A **smart meter** is an electronic device that records information—such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor—and communicates the information to the consumer and electricity suppliers.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) differs from automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The term *smart meter* often refers to an electricity meter, but it also may mean a device measuring natural gas, water or district heating consumption.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] More generally, a smart meter is an electronic device that records information such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meters communicate the information to the consumer for greater clarity of consumption behavior, and electricity suppliers for system monitoring and customer billing.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meters typically record energy near real-time, and report regularly, in short intervals throughout the day.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meters enable two-way communication between the meter and the central system.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meters may be part of a *smart grid*, but do not themselves constitute a smart grid.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) differs from Automated Meter Reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Communications from the meter to the network may be wireless, or via fixed wired connections such as power-line communication (PLC).
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Similar meters, usually referred to as interval or time-of-use meters, have existed for years, but smart meters usually involve real-time or near real-time sensors, power outage notification, and power quality monitoring.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] These additional features are more than simple AMR.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] They are similar in many respects to AMI meters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Interval and time-of-use meters historically have been installed to measure commercial and industrial customers, but may not have automatic reading.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Research by the UK consumer group, showed that as many as one in three confuse smart meters with energy monitors, also known as in-home display monitors.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In 1972, Theodore Paraskevakos, while working with Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system that used digital transmission for security, fire, and medical alarm systems as well as meter reading capabilities.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] This technology was a spin-off from the automatic telephone line identification system, now known as Caller ID.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In 1974, Paraskevakos was awarded a U.S. patent for this technology.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In 1977, he launched Metretek, Inc., which developed and produced the first smart meters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Since this system was developed pre-Internet, Metretek utilized the IBM series 1 mini-computer.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] For this approach, Paraskevakos and Metretek were awarded multiple patents.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The installed base of smart meters in Europe at the end of 2008 was about 39 million units, according to analyst firm Berg Insight.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Globally, Pike Research found that smart meter shipments were 17.4 million units for the first quarter of 2011.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Visiongain determined that the value of the global smart meter market would reach US$7 billion in 2012.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Tahir Mahmood, researchers of University of Engineering & Technology Taxila, Pakistan, introduced the concept of Smart Energy Meters in 2013.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] As of January 2018, over 99 million electricity meters were deployed across the European Union, with an estimated 24 million more to be installed by the end of 2020.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The European Commission DG Energy estimates the 2020 installed base to have required €18.8 billion in investment, growing to €40.7 billion by 2030, with a total deployment of 266 million smart meters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] By the end of 2018, the U.S. had over 86 million smart meters installed.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In 2017, there were 665 million smart meters installed globally.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Revenue generation is expected to grow from $12.8 billion in 2017 to $20 billion by 2022.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Since the inception of electricity deregulation and market-driven pricing throughout the world, utilities have been looking for a means to match consumption with generation.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Non-smart electrical and gas meters only measure total consumption, providing no information of when the energy was consumed.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meters provide a way of measuring electricity consumption in near real-time.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] This allows utility companies to charge different prices for consumption according to the time of day and the season.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] It also facilitates more accurate cash-flow models for utilities.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Since smart meters can be read remotely, labor costs are reduced for utilities.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart metering offers potential benefits to customers.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] With regards to consumption reduction, this is critical for understanding the benefits of smart meters because the relatively small percentage benefits in terms of savings are multiplied by millions of users.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meters for water consumption can also provide detailed and timely information about customer water use and early notification of possible water leaks in their premises.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Electricity consumption, and hence pricing, usually peaks at certain predictable times of the day and the season.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In particular, if generation is constrained, prices can rise when power from other jurisdictions or more costly generation is brought online.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] A 2013 academic study based on existing trials showed that homeowners' electricity consumption on average is reduced by approximately 3-5% when provided with real-time feedback.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Another advantage of smart meters that benefits both customers and the utility is the monitoring capability they provide for the whole electrical system.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] As part of an AMI, utilities can use the real-time data from smart meters measurements related to current, voltage, and power factor to detect system disruptions more quickly, allowing immediate corrective action to minimize customer impact such as blackouts.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meters also help utilities understand the power grid needs with more granularity than legacy meters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] This greater understanding facilitates system planning to meet customer energy needs while reducing the likelihood of additional infrastructure investments, which eliminates unnecessary spending or energy cost increases.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] As a result, smart meters are considered an essential technology to the decarbonisation of the energy system.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Government agencies and utilities are turning toward advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) systems as part of larger "smart grid" initiatives.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] AMI extends automatic meter reading (AMR) technology by providing two-way meter communications, allowing commands to be sent toward the home for multiple purposes, including time-based pricing information, demand-response actions, or remote service disconnects.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Wireless technologies are critical elements of the neighborhood network, aggregating a mesh configuration of up to thousands of meters for back haul to the utility's IT headquarters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The network between the measurement devices and business systems allows the collection and distribution of information to customers, suppliers, utility companies, and service providers.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] This enables these businesses to participate in demand response services.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Consumers can use the information provided by the system to change their normal consumption patterns to take advantage of lower prices.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Pricing can be used to curb the growth of peak demand consumption.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] AMI differs from traditional automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communications with the meter.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Systems only capable of meter readings do not qualify as AMI systems.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Together, these components help utilities and consumers monitor and manage energy use efficiently, supporting smarter grid management.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Communication is a cornerstone of smart meter technology, enabling reliable and secure data transmission to central systems.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] However, the diversity of environments in which smart meters operate presents significant challenges.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] stands out among smart metering connectivity technologies because it leverages existing electrical power infrastructure for data transmission.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Unlike cellular, radio-frequency (RF), or Wi-Fi-based solutions, PLC does not require building or maintaining separate communication networks, making it inherently more cost-effective and easier to scale.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] G3-PLC supports IPv6-based communications and adaptive data rates, providing robust performance even in noisy environments, while PRIME (PoweRline Intelligent Metering Evolution) focuses on efficient, high-speed communication with low-cost implementation.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] like Europe, South America, and parts of Asia where dense infrastructure supports its use.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Utilities favor PLC for its reliability in urban environments and for connecting large numbers of meters within smart grid networks.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] An important feature of G3-PLC and PRIME is their ability to enable mesh networking (also called multi-hop), where smart meters act as repeaters for other meters in the network.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] This functionality allows meters to relay data from neighboring meters to ensure that the information reaches the Data Concentrator Unit (DCU), even if direct communication is not possible due to distance or signal obstructions.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] This approach enhances network reliability and coverage, particularly in dense urban environments or geographically challenging areas.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The challenges faced by rural utilities differ significantly from those of urban counterparts or utilities in remote, mountainous, or poorly serviced areas.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meters often extend their functionality through integration into **Home Area Networks (HANs)**.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Technologies used in HANs vary globally but typically include PLC, wireless ad hoc networks, and Zigbee.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] By leveraging appropriate connectivity solutions, smart meters can address environmental and infrastructural needs while delivering communication and enhanced functionality.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Electricity smart meters start to be utilized as gateways for gas and water meters, creating integrated smart metering systems.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In this configuration, gas and water meters communicate with the electricity meter using Wireless M-Bus (Wireless Meter-Bus), a European standard (EN 13757-4) designed for secure and efficient data transmission between utility meters and data collectors.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The electricity meter then aggregates this data and transmits it to the central utility network via Power Line Communication (PLC), which leverages existing electrical wiring for data transfer.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meter communication protocols are essential for enabling reliable, efficient, and secure data exchange between meters, utilities, and other components of advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] These protocols address the diverse requirements of global markets, supporting various communication methods, from optical ports and serial connections to power line communication (PLC) and wireless networks.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Below is an overview of key protocols, including ANSI standards widely used in North America, IEC protocols prevalent in Europe, the globally recognized OSGP for smart grid applications, and the PLC-focused Meters and More, each designed to meet specific needs in energy monitoring and management.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] "IEC 62056 is the most widely adopted protocol" for smart meter communication, enabling reliable, two-way data exchange within Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) systems.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] It encompasses the DLMS/COSEM protocol for structuring and managing metering data.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] "It is widely used because of its flexibility, scalability, and ability to support different communication media such as Power Line Communication (PLC), TCP/IP, and wireless networks.".
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] It also supports data transmission over serial connections using ASCII or binary formats, with physical media options such as modulated light (via LED and photodiode) or wired connections (typically EIA-485).
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] ANSI C12.18 is an ANSI Standard that describes a protocol used for two-way communications with a meter, mostly used in North American markets.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The C12.18 Standard is written specifically for meter communications via an ANSI Type 2 Optical Port, and specifies lower-level protocol details.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] ANSI C12.19 specifies the data tables that are used.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] ANSI C12.21 is an extension of C12.18 written for modem instead of optical communications, so it is better suited to automatic meter reading.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] ANSI C12.22 is the communication protocol for remote communications.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The Open Smart Grid Protocol (OSGP) is a family of specifications published by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) used in conjunction with the ISO/IEC 14908 control networking standard for smart metering and smart grid applications.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Millions of smart meters based on OSGP are deployed worldwide.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] On July 15, 2015, the OSGP Alliance announced the release of a new security protocol (OSGP-AES-128-PSK) and its availability from OSGP vendors.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] This deprecated the original OSGP-RC4-PSK security protocol which had been identified to be vulnerable.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] "Meters and More was created in 2010 from the coordinated work between Enel and Endesa to adopt, maintain and evolve the field-proven Meters and More open communication protocol for smart grid solutions." .
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In 2010, the Meters and More Association was established to promote the protocol globally, ensuring interoperability and efficiency in power line communication (PLC)-based smart metering systems.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Meters and More is an open communication protocol designed for advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] It facilitates reliable, high-speed data exchange over PLC networks, focusing on energy monitoring, demand response, and secure two-way communication between utilities and consumers.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Unlike DLMS/COSEM, which is a globally standardized and versatile protocol supporting multiple utilities (electricity, gas, and water), Meters and More is tailored specifically for PLC-based systems, emphasizing efficiency, reliability, and ease of deployment in electricity metering.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] There is a growing trend toward the use of TCP/IP technology as a common communication platform for Smart Meter applications, so that utilities can deploy multiple communication systems, while using IP technology as a common management platform.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] A universal metering interface would allow for development and mass production of smart meters and smart grid devices prior to the communication standards being set, and then for the relevant communication modules to be easily added or switched when they are.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] This would lower the risk of investing in the wrong standard as well as permit a single product to be used globally even if regional communication standards vary.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI), the server infrastructure is crucial for managing, storing, and processing the large volumes of data generated by smart meters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] This infrastructure ensures seamless communication between smart meters, utility providers, and end-users, supporting real-time monitoring, billing, and grid management.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] A Data Concentrator Unit (DCU) aggregates data from multiple smart meters within a localized area (e.g., a neighborhood or building) before transmitting it to the central server.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Data concentrators reduce the communication load on the network and help overcome connectivity challenges by acting as intermediaries between smart meters and the head-end system (HES).
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The HES is responsible for collecting, validating, and managing data received from data concentrators and smart meters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] It serves as the central communication hub, facilitating two-way communication between the smart meters and the utility's central servers.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The HES supports meter configuration, firmware updates, and real-time data retrieval, ensuring data integrity and security.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] is a specialized software platform that stores and processes large volumes of meter data collected by the HES.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Key functions of the MDMS include data validation, estimation, and editing, as well as billing preparation, load analysis, and anomaly detection.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] ), and demand response systems, to enable efficient energy management.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Data analytics for smart meters leverages machine learning to extract insights from energy consumption data.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Key applications include demand forecasting, dynamic pricing, Energy Disaggregation, and fault detection, enabling optimized grid performance and personalized energy management.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] These techniques drive efficiency, cost savings, and sustainability in modern energy systems.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] "Energy Disaggregation, or the breakdown of your energy use based on specific appliances or devices", is an exploratory technique for analyzing energy consumption in households, commercial buildings, and industrial settings.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] By using data from a single energy meter, it employs algorithms and machine learning to estimate individual appliance usage without separate monitors.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Known as Non-Intrusive Load Monitoring (NILM), this emerging method offers insights into energy efficiency, helping users optimize usage and reduce costs.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] While promising, energy disaggregation is still being refined for accuracy and scalability as part of smart energy management innovations.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The other critical technology for smart meter systems is the information technology at the utility that integrates the Smart Meter networks with utility applications, such as billing and CIS.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] This includes the Meter Data Management system.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] It also is essential for smart grid implementations that power line communication (PLC) technologies used within the home over a Home Area Network (HAN), are standardized and compatible.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The HAN allows HVAC systems and other household appliances to communicate with the smart meter, and from there to the utility.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Currently there are several broadband or narrowband standards in place, or being developed, that are not yet compatible.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] To address this issue in the United States, the National Institute for Standards and Technology (NIST) established the PAP15 group, which studies and recommends coexistence mechanisms with a focus on the harmonization of PLC Standards for the HAN.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The objective of the group is to ensure that all PLC technologies selected for the HAN coexist as a minimum.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The two leading broadband PLC technologies selected are the HomePlug AV / IEEE 1901 and ITU-T G.hn technologies.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Technical working groups within these organizations are working to develop appropriate coexistence mechanisms.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The HomePlug Powerline Alliance has developed a new standard for smart grid HAN communications called the HomePlug Green PHY specification.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] It is interoperable and coexistent with the widely deployed HomePlug AV technology and with the latest IEEE 1901 global Standard and is based on Broadband OFDM technology.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] ITU-T commissioned in 2010 a new project called G.hnem, to address the home networking aspects of energy management, built upon existing Low Frequency Narrowband OFDM technologies.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Some groups have expressed concerns regarding the cost, health, fire risk, security and privacy effects of smart meters and the remote controllable "kill switch" that is included with most of them.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Many of these concerns regard wireless-only smart meters with no home energy monitoring or control or safety features.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Metering-only solutions, while popular with utilities because they fit existing business models and have cheap up-front capital costs, often result in such "backlash".
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Often the entire smart grid and smart building concept is discredited in part by confusion about the difference between home control and home area network technology and AMI.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The (now former) attorney general of Connecticut has stated that he does not believe smart meters provide any financial benefit to consumers, however, the cost of the installation of the new system is absorbed by those customers.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meters expose the power grid to cyberattacks that could lead to power outages, both by cutting off people's electricity and by overloading the grid.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] However many cybersecurity experts state that smart meters of the UK and Germany have relatively high cybersecurity and that any such attack there would thus require extraordinarily high efforts or financial resources.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The EU Cybersecurity Act took effect in June 2019, which includes Directive on Security Network and Information Systems establishing notification and security requirements for operators of essential services.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Through the Smartgrid Cybersecurity Committee, the U.S.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Department of Energy published cybersecurity guidelines for grid operators in 2010 and updated them in 2014.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Implementing security protocols that protect these devices from malicious attacks has been problematic, due to their limited computational resources and long operational life.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The current version of IEC 62056 includes the possibility to encrypt, authenticate, or sign the meter data.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] One proposed smart meter data verification method involves analyzing the network traffic in real-time to detect anomalies using an Intrusion Detection System (IDS).
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] By identifying exploits as they are being leveraged by attackers, an IDS mitigates the suppliers' risks of energy theft by consumers and denial-of-service attacks by hackers.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Energy utilities must choose between a centralized IDS, embedded IDS, or dedicated IDS depending on the individual needs of the utility.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Researchers have found that for a typical advanced metering infrastructure, the centralized IDS architecture is superior in terms of cost efficiency and security gains.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In the United Kingdom, the Data Communication Company, which transports the commands from the supplier to the smart meter, performs an additional anomaly check on commands issued (and signed) by the energy supplier.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] According to a report published by Brian Krebs, in 2009 a Puerto Rico electricity supplier asked the FBI to investigate large-scale thefts of electricity related to its smart meters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The FBI found that former employees of the power company and the company that made the meters were being paid by consumers to reprogram the devices to show incorrect results, as well as teaching people how to do it themselves.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Several hacking tools that allow security researchers and penetration testers verify the security of electric utility smart meters have been released so far.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Most health concerns about the meters arise from the pulsed radiofrequency (RF) radiation emitted by wireless smart meters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Members of the California State Assembly asked the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST) to study the issue of potential health impacts from smart meters, in particular whether current FCC standards are protective of public health.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The CCST report in April 2011 found no health impacts, based both on lack of scientific evidence of harmful effects from radio frequency (RF) waves and that the RF exposure of people in their homes to smart meters is likely to be minuscule compared to RF exposure to cell phones and microwave ovens.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Daniel Hirsch, retired director of the Program on Environmental and Nuclear Policy at UC Santa Cruz, criticized the CCST report on the grounds that it did not consider studies that suggest the potential for non-thermal health effects such as latent cancers from RF exposure.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) has adopted recommended Permissible Exposure Limit (PEL) for all RF transmitters (including smart meters) operating at frequencies of 300 kHz to 100 GHz.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] These limits, based on field strength and power density, are below the levels of RF radiation that are hazardous to human health.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Other studies substantiate the finding of the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST).
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In 2011, the Electric Power Research Institute performed a study to gauge human exposure to smart meters as compared to the FCC PEL.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The report found that most smart meters only transmit RF signals 1% of the time or less.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] At this rate, and at a distance of 1 foot from the meter, RF exposure would be at a rate of 0.14% of the FCC PEL.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] An indirect potential for harm to health by smart meters is that they enable energy companies to disconnect consumers remotely, typically in response to difficulties with payment.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] This can cause health problems to vulnerable people in financial difficulty; in addition to denial of heat, lighting, and use of appliances, there are people who depend on power to use medical equipment essential for life.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] While there may be legal protections in place to protect the vulnerable, many people in the UK were disconnected in violation of the rules.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Issues surrounding smart meters causing fires have been reported, particularly involving the manufacturer Sensus.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] PECO Energy Company replaced the Sensus meters it had deployed in the Philadelphia, US region after reports that a number of the units had overheated and caused fires.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In July 2014, SaskPower, the province-run utility company of the Canadian province of Saskatchewan, halted its roll-out of Sensus meters after similar, isolated incidents were discovered.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Shortly afterward, Portland General Electric announced that it would replace 70,000 smart meters that had been deployed in the state of Oregon after similar reports.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The company noted that it had been aware of the issues since at least 2013, and they were limited to specific models it had installed between 2010 and 2012.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] On July 30, 2014, after a total of eight recent fire incidents involving the meters, SaskPower was ordered by the Government of Saskatchewan to immediately end its smart meter program, and remove the 105,000 smart meters it had installed.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] One technical reason for privacy concerns is that these meters send detailed information about how much electricity is being used each time.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] More frequent reports provide more detailed information.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Infrequent reports may be of little benefit for the provider, as it doesn't allow as good demand management in the response of changing needs for electricity.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] On the other hand, widespread reports would allow the utility company to infer behavioral patterns for the occupants of a house, such as when the members of the household are probably asleep or absent.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Furthermore, the fine-grained information collected by smart meters raises growing concerns of privacy invasion due to personal behavior exposure (private activity, daily routine, etc.).
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Current trends are to increase the frequency of reports.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] A solution that benefits both provider and user privacy would be to adapt the interval dynamically.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Another solution involves energy storage installed at the household used to reshape the energy consumption profile.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In British Columbia the electric utility is government-owned and as such must comply with privacy laws that prevent the sale of data collected by smart meters; many parts of the world are serviced by private companies that are able to sell their data.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In Australia debt collectors can make use of the data to know when people are at home.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Used as evidence in a court case in Austin, Texas, police agencies secretly collected smart meter power usage data from thousands of residences to determine which used more power than "typical" to identify marijuana growing operations.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meter power data usage patterns can reveal much more than how much power is being used.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Research has demonstrated that smart meters sampling power levels at two-second intervals can reliably identify when different electrical devices are in use.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Reviews of smart meter programs, moratoriums, delays, and "opt-out" programs are some responses to the concerns of customers and government officials.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In response to residents who did not want a smart meter, in June 2012 a utility in Hawaii changed its smart meter program to "opt out".
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The utility said that once the smart grid installation project is nearing completion, KIUC may convert the deferral policy to an opt-out policy or program and may charge a fee to those members to cover the costs of servicing the traditional meters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Any fee would require approval from the Hawaii Public Utilities Commission.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] After receiving numerous complaints about health, hacking, and privacy concerns with the wireless digital devices, the Public Utility Commission of the US state of Maine voted to allow customers to opt-out of the meter change at the cost of $12 a month.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In Connecticut, another US state to consider smart metering, regulators declined a request by the state's largest utility, Connecticut Light & Power, to install 1.2 million of the devices, arguing that the potential savings in electric bills do not justify the cost.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] CL&P already offers its customers time-based rates.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The state's Attorney General George Jepsen was quoted as saying the proposal would cause customers to spend upwards of $500 million on meters and get few benefits in return, a claim that Connecticut Light & Power disputed.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meters allow dynamic pricing; it has been pointed out that, while this allows prices to be reduced at times of low demand, it can also be used to increase prices at peak times if all consumers have smart meters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Additionally smart meters allow energy suppliers to switch customers to expensive prepay tariffs instantly in case of difficulties paying.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In the UK during a period of very high energy prices from 2021, companies were remotely switching smart meters from a credit tariff to an expensive prepay tariff which disconnects supplies unless credit has been purchased.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] While regulations do not permit this without appropriate precautions to help those in financial difficulties and to protect the vulnerable, the rules were often flouted.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] There are questions about whether electricity is or should be primarily a "when you need it" service where the inconvenience/cost-benefit ratio of time-shifting of loads is poor.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In the Chicago area, Commonwealth Edison ran a test installing smart meters on 8,000 randomly selected households together with variable rates and rebates to encourage cutting back during peak usage.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In *Crain's Chicago Business* article "Smart grid test underwhelms.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In the pilot, few power down to save money.", it was reported that fewer than 9% exhibited any amount of peak usage reduction and that the overall amount of reduction was "statistically insignificant".
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] This was from a report by the Electric Power Research Institute, a utility industry think tank who conducted the study and prepared the report.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] By 2016, the 7 million smart meters in Texas had not persuaded many people to check their energy data as the process was too complicated.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] A report from a parliamentary group in the UK suggests people who have smart meters installed are expected to save an average of £11 annually on their energy bills, much less than originally hoped.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The 2016 cost-benefit analysis was updated in 2019 and estimated a similar average saving.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The Australian Victorian Auditor-General found in 2015 that 'Victoria's electricity consumers will have paid an estimated $2.239 billion for metering services, including the rollout and connection of smart meters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Smart meters can allow real-time pricing, and in theory this could help smooth power consumption as consumers adjust their demand in response to price changes.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In 2013, *Take Back Your Power*, an independent Canadian documentary directed by Josh del Sol was released describing "dirty electricity" and the aforementioned issues with smart meters.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The film explores the various contexts of the health, legal, and economic concerns.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] It features narration from the mayor of Peterborough, Ontario, Daryl Bennett, as well as American researcher De-Kun Li, journalist Blake Levitt, and Dr.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] It won a Leo Award for best feature-length documentary and the Annual Humanitarian Award from Indie Fest the following year.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Citizens Advice said in August 2018 that 80% of people with smart meters were happy with them.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Still, it had 3,000 calls in 2017 about problems.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] These related to first-generation smart meters losing their functionality, aggressive sales practices, and still having to send smart meter readings.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Ross Anderson of the Foundation for Information Policy Research has criticised the UK's program on the grounds that it is unlikely to lower energy consumption, is rushed and expensive, and does not promote metering competition.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The high number of SMETS1 meters installed has been criticized by Peter Earl, head of energy at the price comparison website comparethemarket.com.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] UK smart meters in southern England and the Midlands use the mobile phone network to communicate, so they do not work correctly when phone coverage is weak.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] A solution has been proposed, but was not operational as of March 2017.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In March 2018 the National Audit Office (NAO), which watches over public spending, opened an investigation into the smart meter program, which had cost £11bn by then, paid for by electricity users through higher bills.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The National Audit Office published the findings of its investigation in a report titled "Rolling out smart meters" published in November 2018.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The report, amongst other findings, indicated that the number of smart meters installed in the UK would fall materially short of the Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy (BEIS) original ambitions of all UK consumers having a smart meter installed by 2020.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] In September 2019, smart meter rollout in the UK was delayed for four years.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] Ross Anderson and Alex Henney wrote that "Ed Miliband cooked the books" to make a case for smart meters appear economically viable.
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] They say that the first three cost-benefit analyses of residential smart meters found that it would cost more than it would save, but "ministers kept on trying until they got a positive result...
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] To achieve 'profitability' the previous government stretched the assumptions shamelessly".
[src:demand-response-systems/smart-meter] The Employment Appeal Tribunal found that the law was in contravention of the European Convention on Human Rights.
